About open sourcing

The idea of publishing work openly can certainly help establish prior art, encourage collaboration, and make knowledge broadly available.

One thing to keep in mind is that open source is not the same as preventing others from commercializing ideas. Whether you can stop someone from monopolizing or asserting exclusive rights depends on the type of intellectual property, the specific license you choose, and the applicable law. Open publication can sometimes make it harder for others to patent the same disclosed invention because it becomes prior art, but it doesn’t automatically give you the ability to sue everyone who builds on similar concepts.

If part of the Pantheon’s mission is to keep core ideas broadly accessible, it would be worth being deliberate about governance:

* Which parts are intended to remain a commons?
* Which licenses encourage sharing while preventing unwanted restrictions?
* Which pieces, if any, should be commercial to fund continued development?

That way the governance model reinforces the philosophy instead of relying on assumptions about how IP law works.